34
00:02:45,467 --> 00:02:46,833
-Flight's at midday,

35
00:02:46,967 --> 00:02:48,767
so I should be back in London
this evening, sir.

36
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:50,500
-I thought you were
taking the week.

37
00:02:50,633 --> 00:02:53,233
-Aye, well, change of plan.

38
00:02:53,367 --> 00:02:54,833
-What happened?

39
00:02:54,967 --> 00:02:56,200
-Me, basically.

40
00:02:56,333 --> 00:02:57,233
[ Mobile vibrates ]

41
00:02:57,367 --> 00:02:59,700
[ Sighs ] Hold on.

42
00:03:01,067 --> 00:03:02,167
Hello?

43
00:03:02,300 --> 00:03:04,400
-[ Sobbing ] Ruth?

44
00:03:04,533 --> 00:03:07,167
-James, are you all right?

45
00:03:07,300 --> 00:03:09,567
-[ Sobs ] It's Cal.

46
00:03:09,700 --> 00:03:11,133
-What do you mean it's Cal?

47
00:03:11,267 --> 00:03:13,133
-[ Sobbing ]

48
00:03:13,267 --> 00:03:15,067
-James, what is going on?

49
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:16,133
[ Knock on door ]

50
00:03:16,267 --> 00:03:23,667
♪♪

51
00:03:23,800 --> 00:03:31,067
♪♪

52
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:38,600
♪♪

53
00:03:38,733 --> 00:03:46,067
♪♪

54
00:03:46,133 --> 00:03:47,500
[ Police radio chatter ]

55
00:03:47,633 --> 00:03:49,500
[ Breathing heavily ]

56
00:03:52,467 --> 00:03:55,867
-DI Calder. No,
you don't want to see him.

57
00:03:56,067 --> 00:04:01,233
♪♪

58
00:04:01,367 --> 00:04:02,267
-[ Gasps ]

59
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:07,300
♪♪

60
00:04:07,433 --> 00:04:09,300
-There was nothing
they could do.

61
00:04:09,433 --> 00:04:17,667
♪♪

62
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:25,900
♪♪

63
00:04:26,067 --> 00:04:26,967
-[ Shudders ]

64
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:31,533
♪♪

65
00:04:31,667 --> 00:04:33,333
-Why did you let her
near the body?

66
00:04:33,467 --> 00:04:34,933
-Well, I tried to stop her.

67
00:04:35,067 --> 00:04:36,967
-How is she now?

68
00:04:37,100 --> 00:04:39,667
-[ Sighs ] She's in shock.

69
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:41,667
-Do they know
what happened?

70
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:43,733
-Traffic team are only
getting started,

71
00:04:43,867 --> 00:04:45,933
but it looks like
he just went off the road.

72
00:04:46,067 --> 00:04:46,967
-How?

73
00:04:47,100 --> 00:04:48,533
-We don't know,

74
00:04:48,667 --> 00:04:51,100
but Cora thinks she smelled
alcohol on the body.

75
00:04:51,233 --> 00:04:54,900
-[ Sighs ] Okay.

76
00:04:55,067 --> 00:04:56,633
Let Traffic do their work.

77
00:04:56,767 --> 00:04:59,167
Tell 'em to call me as soon as
they have something to report.

78
00:04:59,300 --> 00:05:02,567
And get Ruth
away from there.

79
00:05:05,600 --> 00:05:08,067
Everything we've learned
about Ellen suggests

80
00:05:08,167 --> 00:05:12,400
she was struggling emotionally
before she left for London.

81
00:05:12,533 --> 00:05:14,367
We're trying
to work out why.

82
00:05:14,500 --> 00:05:18,967
-Well, as I said, Ellen's
lifestyle was pretty intense.

83
00:05:19,100 --> 00:05:20,633
Drink, drugs...

84
00:05:20,767 --> 00:05:22,167
-No, I -- I get that.

85
00:05:22,300 --> 00:05:25,733
But I'm starting to think
that the partying

86
00:05:25,867 --> 00:05:30,067
may have been more
of a symptom than the cause.

87
00:05:30,167 --> 00:05:33,400
I wonder if the cause...

88
00:05:33,533 --> 00:05:35,933
may have been
Akmal's death.

89
00:05:37,633 --> 00:05:39,267
-What makes you think that?

90
00:05:39,400 --> 00:05:41,500
-Well, we have
a witness who says

91
00:05:41,633 --> 00:05:45,967
that Ellen's problems began
just after Akmal died.

92
00:05:46,100 --> 00:05:48,867
-Well, the timing
could just be a coincidence.

93
00:05:49,067 --> 00:05:52,533
Perhaps Ellen was going through
something else at that time.

94
00:05:52,667 --> 00:05:56,067
-Mm-hmm. Could be.

95
00:05:56,200 --> 00:06:00,600
Did Ellen ever meet Akmal
when she was working here?

96
00:06:02,133 --> 00:06:03,400
-I suppose she must have,

97
00:06:03,533 --> 00:06:05,067
but then, she only did
a couple of shifts.

98
00:06:05,167 --> 00:06:06,400
And when she was here,

99
00:06:06,533 --> 00:06:08,833
she barely gave Akmal
a second look.

100
00:06:08,967 --> 00:06:12,067
-So, there was no...
connection?

101
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:13,833
-None that I saw.

102
00:06:13,967 --> 00:06:17,167
-But that doesn't mean
she wasn't affected by it.

103
00:06:17,300 --> 00:06:19,767
Lots of people were.

104
00:06:19,900 --> 00:06:22,333
The kindness
of the people here,

105
00:06:22,467 --> 00:06:25,767
it's what's
helped us through.

106
00:06:25,900 --> 00:06:27,967
-But when she was
in Langbank,

107
00:06:28,100 --> 00:06:31,333
Ellen never mentioned
Akmal to you?

108
00:06:31,467 --> 00:06:33,700
-Never.

109
00:06:35,467 --> 00:06:37,667
-Okay. [ Chuckles ]

110
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:39,700
Well, it was just a theory.

111
00:06:39,833 --> 00:06:42,867
I really am sorry for
bringing it all back up again.

112
00:06:43,067 --> 00:06:44,533
-It's fine.

113
00:06:44,667 --> 00:06:46,500
-I'll see myself out.

114
00:06:50,067 --> 00:06:51,333
[ Door opens, closes ]

115
00:06:51,467 --> 00:06:55,900
♪♪

116
00:06:56,067 --> 00:06:58,933
-[ Breathes deeply ]

117
00:06:59,067 --> 00:07:02,233
-I am sorry.

118
00:07:02,367 --> 00:07:04,767
I really am.

119
00:07:07,567 --> 00:07:08,867
Cal was a good guy.

120
00:07:09,067 --> 00:07:10,600
[ Mobile chimes ]

121
00:07:10,733 --> 00:07:14,200
Bit of a rogue maybe, but...

122
00:07:14,333 --> 00:07:16,567
he had a good heart.

123
00:07:17,967 --> 00:07:19,500
I mean, I'm not saying
me and him got on --

124
00:07:19,633 --> 00:07:21,500
-Shh. Shut up a minute.
-Hey, it's me.

125
00:07:21,633 --> 00:07:23,467
Just been up
to see Bobby Bain.

126
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:25,400
Definitely something
going on there.

127
00:07:25,533 --> 00:07:26,467
Call me back.

128
00:07:26,600 --> 00:07:28,467
-[ Gasps softly ]

129
00:07:29,733 --> 00:07:31,933
We need to go to the Bains.

130
00:07:38,967 --> 00:07:40,767
-Morning.

131
00:07:40,900 --> 00:07:45,967
-Where's your mum and dad?
-Still sleeping.

132
00:07:46,100 --> 00:07:48,367
-[ Snaps fingers ] Hey.

133
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:50,667
You hungry?

134
00:07:50,800 --> 00:07:51,933
Head up to the big house.

135
00:07:52,067 --> 00:07:54,067
Your gran'll make
some breakfast.

136
00:08:03,533 --> 00:08:06,200
-[ Groans ]

137
00:08:06,333 --> 00:08:08,867
Jesus.

138
00:08:09,067 --> 00:08:13,367
I forgot how comfortable
this bed was.

139
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:15,567
What time is it?

140
00:08:20,233 --> 00:08:23,200
You okay?

141
00:08:23,333 --> 00:08:27,300
-I was thinking about
the day she was born.

142
00:08:27,433 --> 00:08:29,900
[ Chuckles ]

143
00:08:30,067 --> 00:08:33,267
14 hours in labour.

144
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,500
I thought she was
never coming out.

145
00:08:37,967 --> 00:08:41,167
-Sure Ellen was always
hard work.

146
00:08:41,300 --> 00:08:43,133
-She was.

147
00:08:47,100 --> 00:08:50,833
Were you shocked?

148
00:08:50,967 --> 00:08:52,767
-What?

149
00:08:52,900 --> 00:08:55,067
-Ellen...

150
00:08:55,200 --> 00:08:57,400
When they told you
she was dead, were you shocked?

151
00:08:57,533 --> 00:09:00,800
-Jesus Christ.

152
00:09:00,933 --> 00:09:02,967
What kind
of a question is that?

153
00:09:03,100 --> 00:09:05,700
-Because I wasn't.

154
00:09:08,967 --> 00:09:14,067
I mean...
I felt numb and...

155
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:15,767
you know, grief, anger.

156
00:09:15,900 --> 00:09:17,367
I mean, I f--

157
00:09:17,500 --> 00:09:21,200
I felt all the things
I was supposed to feel, but...

158
00:09:21,333 --> 00:09:22,567
[ Chuckles ]

159
00:09:22,700 --> 00:09:25,733
I wasn't surprised.

160
00:09:25,867 --> 00:09:32,667
You know, I thought, "Well, aye.
Aye, that makes sense."

161
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:34,533
-Ellen didn't
deserve to die.

162
00:09:34,667 --> 00:09:36,467
-No, I didn't --

163
00:09:36,600 --> 00:09:39,567
I didn't say
she deserved it.

164
00:09:39,700 --> 00:09:42,267
[ Sighs ] She was so...

165
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:44,867
She was so reckless.

166
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:48,767
[ Vehicle approaching ]

167
00:09:51,667 --> 00:09:53,733
Someone's here.

168
00:09:55,133 --> 00:09:56,767
[ Door opens ]

169
00:09:56,900 --> 00:09:58,233
[ Sheep bleating ]

170
00:09:58,367 --> 00:10:03,633
♪♪

171
00:10:03,767 --> 00:10:08,833
♪♪

172
00:10:08,967 --> 00:10:10,067
-Can I help you?

173
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:11,433
-Well, you can start
by telling us

174
00:10:11,567 --> 00:10:14,533
why Cal Innes
was with you last night.

175
00:10:14,667 --> 00:10:16,300
-Well, he popped by
for a few drinks.

176
00:10:16,433 --> 00:10:21,133
-Cal Innes... popped by...
to see you?

177
00:10:21,267 --> 00:10:22,400
-That's right.

178
00:10:22,533 --> 00:10:24,100
-Didn't realise
you were pals.

179
00:10:24,233 --> 00:10:25,533
-[ Scoffs ] Did you not?

180
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:27,200
-Well, as far
as I remember it,

181
00:10:27,333 --> 00:10:30,533
you two couldn't stand
each other back in the day.

182
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:34,333
-What's the issue here?

183
00:10:34,467 --> 00:10:37,233
-Cal's van went off
the road last night.

184
00:10:37,367 --> 00:10:39,033
Just outside of Aith.

185
00:10:39,167 --> 00:10:41,200
-God. Is he all right?

186
00:10:41,333 --> 00:10:43,833
-He's dead.

187
00:10:43,967 --> 00:10:46,500
-Jesus.

188
00:10:46,633 --> 00:10:49,233
I mean, that's awful.
I'm sorry.

189
00:10:49,367 --> 00:10:51,667
How long was he here
for last night?

190
00:10:51,800 --> 00:10:55,233
-Arrived about seven.
Must've left... just before 11.

191
00:10:55,367 --> 00:10:57,700
-So, that's four hours
drinking, then?

192
00:10:57,833 --> 00:11:00,367
-And talking.
-About what?

193
00:11:01,400 --> 00:11:03,633
-Mostly he talked
about you.

194
00:11:03,767 --> 00:11:05,633
-How much did Cal
have to drink?

195
00:11:05,767 --> 00:11:08,933
-Not sure I should answer that.
-Yes, you fucking should!

196
00:11:09,733 --> 00:11:11,600
[ Breathes deeply ]

197
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:17,433
-I'd say he had a fair few
before he left.

198
00:11:17,567 --> 00:11:19,533
-And you just
let him drive?

199
00:11:19,667 --> 00:11:21,667
-I told him not to,
I told him to stay the night,

200
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:23,533
but he was having
none of it.

201
00:11:23,667 --> 00:11:26,267
-What did you do
after he left?

202
00:11:26,400 --> 00:11:28,867
-Crashed out
in the workshop.

203
00:11:29,067 --> 00:11:33,200
-Anybody vouch for you?

204
00:11:33,333 --> 00:11:35,400
-No.

205
00:11:35,533 --> 00:11:37,133
-Why does he need
someone to vouch for him

206
00:11:37,267 --> 00:11:39,233
if it was an accident?

207
00:11:39,367 --> 00:11:45,367
♪♪

208
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:47,933
What was he doing here?

209
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:51,933
-We need to go
to the station.

210
00:11:52,067 --> 00:11:55,433
-I'm not sure
that's a good idea.

211
00:11:55,567 --> 00:11:59,067
[ Sighs ] Maybe
we could call in.

212
00:12:00,700 --> 00:12:02,967
[ Car lock beeps ]

213
00:12:03,100 --> 00:12:05,067
-If you can do an extra
couple of hours on Friday,

214
00:12:05,167 --> 00:12:06,067
that would be great.

215
00:12:06,200 --> 00:12:09,567
-Yep. No problem.

216
00:12:09,700 --> 00:12:11,767
I heard about Cal.
You okay?

217
00:12:11,900 --> 00:12:14,300
-I'm fine.
It's Ruth I'm worried about.

218
00:12:14,433 --> 00:12:16,700
Sandy said she turned up
at the accident site.

219
00:12:16,833 --> 00:12:19,533
Saw the body.
-Do we know how it happened?

220
00:12:19,667 --> 00:12:21,667
-Cora thinks
Cal had been drinking.

221
00:12:21,800 --> 00:12:24,333
-[ Sighs ] Is there anyone
with Ruth?

222
00:12:24,467 --> 00:12:27,300
-I asked Sandy
to look after her.

223
00:12:27,433 --> 00:12:28,933
-Sandy?

224
00:12:29,067 --> 00:12:30,800
-There was no-one else.

225
00:12:30,933 --> 00:12:33,933
-Better than nothing,
I suppose.

226
00:12:34,067 --> 00:12:37,400
Aye, and there's that.

227
00:12:37,533 --> 00:12:39,333
-Where are they now?

228
00:12:39,467 --> 00:12:40,767
-Rosemary was bailed
this morning.

229
00:12:40,900 --> 00:12:42,700
She's staying at her mum's.

230
00:12:42,833 --> 00:12:44,633
Ayre's on his way
to Peterhead.

231
00:12:44,767 --> 00:12:46,333
They'll hold him there
until his trial.

232
00:12:46,467 --> 00:12:48,800
-Tosh, can I speak to you?

233
00:12:48,933 --> 00:12:52,367
-Sure. Get Uniform to do
a welfare check on Rosemary,

234
00:12:52,500 --> 00:12:54,700
just in case there's
any backlash from this.

235
00:12:54,833 --> 00:12:55,933
-Will do.

236
00:12:59,433 --> 00:13:01,067
-All we know right now

237
00:13:01,133 --> 00:13:03,900
is Cal's van went off the road
sometime last night.

238
00:13:04,067 --> 00:13:05,500
Doesn't look like
any other vehicles were --

239
00:13:05,633 --> 00:13:07,967
-Did you speak
with the Sadats?

240
00:13:08,100 --> 00:13:09,433
-This morning. Why?

241
00:13:09,567 --> 00:13:12,567
-What happened?
-Nothing.

242
00:13:12,700 --> 00:13:15,967
I was following up on a theory
about Ellen and Akmal.

243
00:13:16,100 --> 00:13:18,467
Why? What's the problem?

244
00:13:18,600 --> 00:13:19,767
-[ Breathes deeply ]

245
00:13:19,900 --> 00:13:22,067
Their solicitor
just called.

246
00:13:22,200 --> 00:13:23,533
It seems Azir
and Farida felt

247
00:13:23,667 --> 00:13:25,700
that you were aggressive
in your questioning

248
00:13:25,833 --> 00:13:28,733
and caused them
undue distress.

249
00:13:28,867 --> 00:13:31,900
-Okay, that is not
what happened.

250
00:13:32,067 --> 00:13:34,533
-Well, the solicitor's
threatening a formal complaint.

251
00:13:34,667 --> 00:13:36,500
And she says she wants
all future contact

252
00:13:36,633 --> 00:13:38,967
to be made through her.

253
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:40,167
You need to back off a bit.

254
00:13:40,300 --> 00:13:41,733
-Hang on.

255
00:13:41,867 --> 00:13:44,100
They must've made that call
the minute I left.

256
00:13:44,233 --> 00:13:47,200
-Suggests they were upset.

257
00:13:47,333 --> 00:13:50,867
-I need to see the report
on the Akmal Sadat accident.

258
00:13:51,067 --> 00:13:52,167
-Why?

259
00:13:52,300 --> 00:13:54,667
-If the Sadats
are calling in lawyers,

260
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:57,600
they're hiding something.

261
00:13:57,733 --> 00:13:59,467
-What did I just say
about backing off?

262
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:02,633
-I want to see
the report, Harry.

263
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:06,100
-[ Sighs ]

264
00:14:06,233 --> 00:14:14,100
♪♪

265
00:14:14,233 --> 00:14:22,067
♪♪

266
00:14:22,167 --> 00:14:24,200
-Caroline's fixed it.

267
00:14:24,333 --> 00:14:27,167
We won't be getting
any more surprise visits.

268
00:14:27,300 --> 00:14:30,633
-We can't hold them off forever.
-We won't have to.

269
00:14:30,767 --> 00:14:32,667
This will all blow over
in a couple of weeks.

270
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:35,100
-It's not going
to blow over, Azir.

271
00:14:38,267 --> 00:14:40,067
-We just carry on
as normal.

272
00:14:40,200 --> 00:14:42,867
-Normal? There's nothing normal
about any of this.

273
00:14:43,067 --> 00:14:44,133
It's insane.

274
00:14:44,267 --> 00:14:46,500
And I'm not taking those!

275
00:14:46,633 --> 00:14:47,967
You can't keep
numbing me to this.

276
00:14:48,100 --> 00:14:49,767
-I'm just trying
to keep you calm.

277
00:14:49,900 --> 00:14:53,233
-I don't want to be calm!
I'm not like you!

278
00:14:53,367 --> 00:14:55,933
You -- you go around acting
like nothing's happened.

279
00:14:56,067 --> 00:14:59,867
Like a robot!
-What else can I do?!

280
00:15:00,067 --> 00:15:01,633
Huh?

281
00:15:01,767 --> 00:15:05,833
How else am I supposed to get us
out of the mess you put us in?!

282
00:15:07,433 --> 00:15:13,567
If you knew the things
I've had to do to protect you.

283
00:15:14,700 --> 00:15:16,933
The things
I've done for you.

284
00:15:17,067 --> 00:15:22,200
♪♪

285
00:15:22,333 --> 00:15:24,833
I have a meeting.

286
00:15:24,967 --> 00:15:29,400
I need you to stay here
and do nothing. Okay?

287
00:15:29,533 --> 00:15:35,767
♪♪

288
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:36,900
[ Door opens ]

289
00:15:39,067 --> 00:15:40,333
-They lost a kid, Tosh.

290
00:15:40,467 --> 00:15:42,333
If it were me,
the last thing I'd want

291
00:15:42,467 --> 00:15:44,333
is for it all to be
dragged up again.

292
00:15:44,467 --> 00:15:45,933
-But to call in
their lawyer?

293
00:15:46,067 --> 00:15:47,700
-Okay, granted,
it's a bit extreme,

294
00:15:47,833 --> 00:15:50,067
but then, you know,
maybe they felt you were...

295
00:15:50,133 --> 00:15:52,600
-What? Doing my job?

296
00:15:52,733 --> 00:15:54,867
-Look, I'm just saying.

297
00:15:55,067 --> 00:15:57,133
There's a lot of folk
who feel for Farida and Azir.

298
00:15:57,267 --> 00:16:00,200
-Your little harem?
-No, not just the nursery mums.

299
00:16:00,333 --> 00:16:02,233
Half the Isles turned out
for the memorial.

300
00:16:02,367 --> 00:16:04,133
-Look, I cannot
just drop this

301
00:16:04,267 --> 00:16:06,067
because people
feel sorry for them.

302
00:16:06,133 --> 00:16:09,933
-Yeah, I know, but...
maybe go gently, eh?

303
00:16:10,067 --> 00:16:12,333
[ Door opens, closes ]
Like, we have to live here.

304
00:16:12,467 --> 00:16:14,467
-I'll talk to you later.

305
00:16:14,600 --> 00:16:17,800
Ruth, I'm so sorry
about Cal.

306
00:16:17,933 --> 00:16:20,067
-You need to bring in
Bobby Bain.

307
00:16:20,200 --> 00:16:21,333
-Okay, why?

308
00:16:21,467 --> 00:16:23,367
-Because he was
with Cal last night.

309
00:16:23,500 --> 00:16:24,767
-They were drinking
at the farm.

310
00:16:24,900 --> 00:16:28,300
-Not just drinking.
Listen...

311
00:16:28,433 --> 00:16:31,933
-Hey, it's me.
Just been up to see Bobby Bain.

312
00:16:32,067 --> 00:16:33,867
Definitely something
going on there.

313
00:16:34,067 --> 00:16:36,567
Call me back.
-When did Cal leave this?

314
00:16:36,700 --> 00:16:38,267
-Last night,
after he left the farm.

315
00:16:38,400 --> 00:16:39,800
-Did you call him back?

316
00:16:39,933 --> 00:16:42,467
-I didn't pick it up
until this morning.

317
00:16:42,600 --> 00:16:45,433
Point is, Cal found out
something about Bobby,

318
00:16:45,567 --> 00:16:48,700
and Bobby was shifty
when we spoke to him.

319
00:16:50,300 --> 00:16:52,133
-When?
-What?

320
00:16:52,267 --> 00:16:54,133
-When did you speak
to Bobby?

321
00:16:54,267 --> 00:16:55,833
-This morning.

322
00:16:55,967 --> 00:16:57,667
-[ Exhales deeply ]

323
00:16:58,667 --> 00:17:01,067
Could I have a word?

324
00:17:03,367 --> 00:17:06,067
-Ruth, I'm sorry about...

325
00:17:08,933 --> 00:17:11,600
-We're wasting time here.

326
00:17:11,733 --> 00:17:14,467
The sooner we move on Bobby...
-How are you feeling?

327
00:17:14,600 --> 00:17:17,400
-How am I feeling?
-About Cal.

328
00:17:19,100 --> 00:17:20,367
-Well, I'll feel
a whole lot better

329
00:17:20,500 --> 00:17:22,567
when you bring in
Bobby Bain.

330
00:17:22,700 --> 00:17:26,167
-For what?
-For what?!

331
00:17:26,300 --> 00:17:28,167
Did you not hear
the message?

332
00:17:28,300 --> 00:17:29,733
Cal finds out
something about him,

333
00:17:29,867 --> 00:17:32,133
next thing, he's driving
his van off the road?

334
00:17:32,267 --> 00:17:34,300
-Have you spoken to James?

335
00:17:34,433 --> 00:17:36,500
-No, I --
I haven't had time.

336
00:17:36,633 --> 00:17:37,833
-Well, don't you think
maybe you should?

337
00:17:37,967 --> 00:17:40,767
He probably needs
a friend right now.

338
00:17:40,900 --> 00:17:43,067
-I'd rather just focus
on Bobby.

339
00:17:43,200 --> 00:17:45,600
So, are we bringing him in,
or -- or what?

340
00:17:45,733 --> 00:17:47,067
-I think we should wait

341
00:17:47,167 --> 00:17:49,700
for Cora and the Crash
Investigation team.

342
00:17:49,833 --> 00:17:53,533
-Oh, for Christ's sake.
-Ruth, listen to me.

343
00:17:53,667 --> 00:17:56,167
You need to stay
out of this.

344
00:17:57,967 --> 00:17:59,300
-Okay.

345
00:17:59,433 --> 00:18:02,333
Know what? Forget it.

346
00:18:02,467 --> 00:18:04,200
-Ruth?

347
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:08,233
-Lab results on those new pills
show they're pretty high grade.

348
00:18:08,367 --> 00:18:09,667
-And?

349
00:18:09,800 --> 00:18:11,367
-Well, it is unusual
for up here. I mean...

350
00:18:11,500 --> 00:18:13,467
[ Door slams ]

351
00:18:14,967 --> 00:18:17,400
-Sandy, take her
to James Innes.

352
00:18:17,533 --> 00:18:19,733
Stay with her
and keep her out of trouble.

353
00:18:19,867 --> 00:18:21,900
-Sure.

354
00:18:22,067 --> 00:18:24,233
She going to be okay?

355
00:18:24,367 --> 00:18:26,533
-I don't know.

356
00:18:30,233 --> 00:18:31,933
[ Dog barking ]

357
00:18:34,700 --> 00:18:37,067
-Hi. I've got to go.

358
00:18:37,167 --> 00:18:39,533
There's toast and eggs
in the kitchen for you.

359
00:18:39,667 --> 00:18:43,367
-I'm not hungry.

360
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:46,067
-Hey...
-[ Sniffles ]

361
00:18:46,200 --> 00:18:48,167
-What's the matter?

362
00:18:48,300 --> 00:18:51,067
-Just thinking about Ellen.

363
00:18:51,200 --> 00:18:53,233
-[ Sighs ]

364
00:18:53,367 --> 00:18:58,133
I know, I know.
It's awful.

365
00:18:58,267 --> 00:19:01,300
Is there anything I can do?

366
00:19:01,433 --> 00:19:04,067
-Can you transfer me
some money?

367
00:19:04,167 --> 00:19:06,733
-[ Scoffs ] I gave you
30 quid yesterday.

368
00:19:06,867 --> 00:19:09,467
-It's fine, it's fine.
Doesn't matter.

369
00:19:10,567 --> 00:19:11,833
-[ Sighs ]

370
00:19:13,167 --> 00:19:16,667
[ Mobile chimes ]
I'll ping 50 over, okay?

371
00:19:16,800 --> 00:19:19,067
-Thanks.
-But I need to go.

372
00:19:19,133 --> 00:19:22,200
I'll see you later.
-See you.

373
00:19:26,067 --> 00:19:28,767
[ Door opens, closes ]

374
00:19:32,433 --> 00:19:34,733
[ Mobile vibrating ]

375
00:19:39,067 --> 00:19:40,733
-Hello?

376
00:19:40,867 --> 00:19:42,867
-Cal's dead.
-What?

377
00:19:43,067 --> 00:19:46,633
-Last night. Crashed his van
on the way back from the farm.

378
00:19:46,767 --> 00:19:48,700
Police came to see me
about it this morning.

379
00:19:48,833 --> 00:19:51,267
-Why?
-'Cos he was with me last night.

380
00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:52,800
-What do you mean
he was with you?

381
00:19:52,933 --> 00:19:54,567
-Never mind.

382
00:19:54,700 --> 00:19:56,367
There's a good chance
they'll want to speak to you.

383
00:19:56,500 --> 00:19:58,067
If they do,
you don't mention me

384
00:19:58,167 --> 00:19:59,767
and you don't mention
the money.

385
00:19:59,900 --> 00:20:01,967
-Well -- well, what do I say?
-I don't care.

386
00:20:02,100 --> 00:20:03,900
Just as long as you
keep my name out of it.

387
00:20:04,033 --> 00:20:04,933
-Bob, Bob!

388
00:20:05,067 --> 00:20:14,333
♪♪

389
00:20:14,467 --> 00:20:17,967
♪♪

390
00:20:24,033 --> 00:20:26,733
-You don't have to go in
if you don't want to.

391
00:20:26,867 --> 00:20:31,367
I mean, we can just go
somewhere else.

392
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:38,567
You know, when my da died,
I didn't want to talk to anyone.

393
00:20:38,700 --> 00:20:42,567
Just wanted to hide away
from the world.

394
00:20:42,700 --> 00:20:46,267
But the thing about grief is,
it needs to be shared.

395
00:20:46,400 --> 00:20:47,867
You can't do it
on your own.

396
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:50,067
-Jesus! Fine, I'm going.

397
00:20:50,200 --> 00:20:53,067
Anything to shut you up.

398
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:54,733
-[ Sighs ]

399
00:20:56,567 --> 00:20:58,067
-[ Breathes deeply ]

400
00:20:58,200 --> 00:21:03,500
♪♪

401
00:21:03,633 --> 00:21:05,967
[ Police radio chatter ]

402
00:21:06,100 --> 00:21:08,067
[ Quiet, indistinct chatter ]

403
00:21:08,167 --> 00:21:14,300
♪♪

404
00:21:14,433 --> 00:21:22,333
♪♪

405
00:21:22,467 --> 00:21:27,067
♪♪

406
00:21:27,133 --> 00:21:28,133
-Ruth.

407
00:21:28,267 --> 00:21:33,933
♪♪

408
00:21:34,067 --> 00:21:37,767
How did this happen, eh?

409
00:21:40,100 --> 00:21:42,333
What are we going to do?

410
00:21:42,467 --> 00:21:46,367
♪♪

411
00:21:46,500 --> 00:21:47,900
-[ Sobbing ] Come here.

412
00:21:48,067 --> 00:21:49,567
-[ Breathing shakily ]

413
00:21:49,700 --> 00:21:58,100
♪♪

414
00:21:58,233 --> 00:22:08,167
♪♪

415
00:22:08,300 --> 00:22:18,133
♪♪

416
00:22:18,267 --> 00:22:21,533
-Billy?
-Aye?

417
00:22:21,667 --> 00:22:26,100
-Get me Heather Bain's number.

418
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:29,467
-I don't get it.

419
00:22:29,600 --> 00:22:32,067
It's Azir
and Farida's kitchen.

420
00:22:32,200 --> 00:22:33,600
So what?

421
00:22:33,733 --> 00:22:37,600
-On the worktop.
By the fridge.

422
00:22:37,733 --> 00:22:42,167
The cleaning caddy.
Isn't that one of yours?

423
00:22:42,300 --> 00:22:44,067
-Looks like it.

424
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:46,667
Guess I must've
left it there.

425
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:51,300
-But this photograph was taken
on the day of Akmal's accident.

426
00:22:51,433 --> 00:22:53,833
Were you at the Sadats'
house that day?

427
00:22:53,967 --> 00:22:55,400
-No!

428
00:22:55,533 --> 00:22:59,100
But I probably left the caddy
there a few days before.

429
00:23:01,067 --> 00:23:02,767
-Is there any chance

430
00:23:02,900 --> 00:23:06,767
that Ellen was at the Sadats'
house that day?

431
00:23:06,900 --> 00:23:08,600
-Don't see why
she would've been.

432
00:23:08,733 --> 00:23:11,133
-Well, maybe they got her in
for a shift without you knowing.

433
00:23:11,267 --> 00:23:13,800
-[ Scoffs ] I doubt it.
They're not the type.

434
00:23:13,933 --> 00:23:17,733
Plus Ellen was a pretty
useless cleaner.

435
00:23:23,333 --> 00:23:25,967
Why are you asking, anyway?

436
00:23:28,167 --> 00:23:32,400
-I think Akmal's death
had an impact on Ellen.

437
00:23:33,667 --> 00:23:37,533
I think it's the reason
why she was struggling.

438
00:23:37,667 --> 00:23:40,067
Did she ever talk about it?

439
00:23:42,700 --> 00:23:45,933
-Well, aye. For a while, it was
all anyone was talking about.

440
00:23:46,067 --> 00:23:47,933
-Yeah, but beyond that.

441
00:23:48,067 --> 00:23:51,467
Did you ever get the sense
that it was on her mind?

442
00:23:51,600 --> 00:23:54,433
-Ellen wasn't one
for dwelling on sad stuff.

443
00:23:54,567 --> 00:23:58,067
Not when there was a party
or a boy to think about.

444
00:23:58,200 --> 00:24:00,300
-I don't know.

445
00:24:00,433 --> 00:24:04,767
I think Ellen was a lot deeper
than people seem to think.

446
00:24:08,667 --> 00:24:12,200
-Oh! Sorry, I need to go.

447
00:24:12,333 --> 00:24:13,900
I'll tell you what --

448
00:24:14,067 --> 00:24:17,567
I'll check if I'm missing
a caddy when I get home.

449
00:24:17,700 --> 00:24:20,567
-Thanks.
I appreciate that.

450
00:24:23,067 --> 00:24:25,167
[ Door opens, closes ]

451
00:24:26,533 --> 00:24:28,400
[ Mobile dialling ]

452
00:24:28,533 --> 00:24:31,600
-McCabe.
-Hi, Billy, it's me.

453
00:24:31,733 --> 00:24:35,400
Going to need you to pull
some call records for me.

454
00:24:35,533 --> 00:24:39,467
♪♪

455
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:41,900
[ Birds calling ]

456
00:24:50,233 --> 00:24:51,800
-You okay?

457
00:24:51,933 --> 00:24:54,967
-I can't do
other people's grief.

458
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:00,433
-[ Exhales deeply ]

459
00:25:01,933 --> 00:25:03,467
-How is he?

460
00:25:03,600 --> 00:25:06,067
-James? James is...

461
00:25:06,200 --> 00:25:07,567
well, he's wrecked,

462
00:25:07,700 --> 00:25:10,867
but he's got good people
around him.

463
00:25:11,067 --> 00:25:12,900
Unlike you.

464
00:25:13,067 --> 00:25:14,967
-I'm fine.

465
00:25:19,867 --> 00:25:22,767
-Amma's gone
to stay with a pal.

466
00:25:22,900 --> 00:25:26,633
Decided to take
some time out.

467
00:25:26,767 --> 00:25:28,367
-I see.

468
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:31,467
-Just need some space,
you know?

469
00:25:31,600 --> 00:25:33,167
Look, I'm sorry
about the other night.

470
00:25:33,300 --> 00:25:34,600
I was out of order.

471
00:25:34,733 --> 00:25:37,667
-It's okay.
-No, it's not.

472
00:25:37,800 --> 00:25:39,333
It's not. I shouldn't
have reacted like that.

473
00:25:39,467 --> 00:25:42,333
I shouldn't have got angry.

474
00:25:42,467 --> 00:25:44,433
-You and Dad were close.

475
00:25:44,567 --> 00:25:46,467
I get it.

476
00:25:49,300 --> 00:25:51,633
-That's not
why I got angry.

477
00:25:55,467 --> 00:25:57,533
I think you might
be right.

478
00:25:59,500 --> 00:26:02,567
-About what?

479
00:26:02,700 --> 00:26:05,100
-About Dad
and Stella Quinn.

480
00:26:05,233 --> 00:26:10,267
♪♪

481
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:15,433
♪♪

482
00:26:15,567 --> 00:26:20,767
♪♪

483
00:26:20,900 --> 00:26:25,967
♪♪

484
00:26:26,100 --> 00:26:31,133
♪♪

485
00:26:31,267 --> 00:26:36,267
♪♪

486
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:41,600
♪♪

487
00:26:41,733 --> 00:26:46,600
♪♪

488
00:26:46,733 --> 00:26:48,833
-[ Strumming guitar strings ]

489
00:26:48,967 --> 00:26:55,233
♪♪

490
00:26:55,367 --> 00:27:01,833
♪♪

491
00:27:01,967 --> 00:27:08,200
♪♪

492
00:27:08,333 --> 00:27:14,600
♪♪

493
00:27:14,733 --> 00:27:16,967
-And those dates
are confirmed?

494
00:27:17,100 --> 00:27:18,833
-It looks like it.

495
00:27:20,700 --> 00:27:23,667
-What's going on?

496
00:27:23,800 --> 00:27:27,133
-I pulled the call records
for the Sadats

497
00:27:27,267 --> 00:27:28,700
and Heather and Ellen

498
00:27:28,833 --> 00:27:31,233
from around the time
Akmal Sadat died.

499
00:27:31,367 --> 00:27:32,867
-Why?

500
00:27:35,467 --> 00:27:38,333
-Well, because I think there's
something about Akmal's death

501
00:27:38,467 --> 00:27:39,800
they're not telling us,

502
00:27:39,933 --> 00:27:41,767
and I think Heather and Ellen
were involved.

503
00:27:41,900 --> 00:27:43,400
-I --

504
00:27:43,533 --> 00:27:46,433
-Look, just -- just listen to me
just for a minute. Please.

505
00:27:46,567 --> 00:27:48,833
The day after the accident,

506
00:27:48,967 --> 00:27:51,833
Ellen called Heather
seven times.

507
00:27:51,967 --> 00:27:53,333
Now, up until that day,

508
00:27:53,467 --> 00:27:56,533
Heather was lucky to get a call
from Ellen once a week.

509
00:27:56,667 --> 00:27:58,133
Azir's records show

510
00:27:58,267 --> 00:28:01,733
that he and Heather
talked 16 times

511
00:28:01,867 --> 00:28:03,833
in the days
after Akmal's death.

512
00:28:03,967 --> 00:28:06,533
Some of those calls
lasted over an hour,

513
00:28:06,667 --> 00:28:08,233
and Heather claims
neither she nor Ellen

514
00:28:08,367 --> 00:28:11,467
was working at the Sadats' place
on the day of the accident,

515
00:28:11,600 --> 00:28:14,267
but we have her
cleaning caddy at the scene.

516
00:28:14,400 --> 00:28:15,633
What's it doing there?

517
00:28:15,767 --> 00:28:17,933
-Akmal's death was investigated.
-I know.

518
00:28:18,067 --> 00:28:20,067
-Police, pathologist,
child services,

519
00:28:20,133 --> 00:28:25,467
and even my office decided it
was nothing more than a tragedy.

520
00:28:25,600 --> 00:28:28,567
-Maybe you got it wrong.
-Why?

521
00:28:28,700 --> 00:28:31,767
Because of some
unusual call patterns?

522
00:28:31,900 --> 00:28:33,733
A child had died.

523
00:28:33,867 --> 00:28:35,800
It wasn't a normal time
for anyone.

524
00:28:35,933 --> 00:28:41,433
-And for Azir Sadat,
it was the worst time.

525
00:28:41,567 --> 00:28:43,333
The man lost his son.

526
00:28:43,467 --> 00:28:47,367
I can't imagine how I would feel
if that was my child,

527
00:28:47,500 --> 00:28:49,333
but I am pretty sure

528
00:28:49,467 --> 00:28:52,833
the last person I'd be calling
in the days after it

529
00:28:52,967 --> 00:28:54,433
is my cleaner.

530
00:28:54,567 --> 00:28:56,467
-I think you need to focus
on who killed Ellen Quinn.

531
00:28:56,600 --> 00:28:58,100
-Harry, I am!

532
00:28:58,233 --> 00:29:01,133
We know Ellen was struggling
before she went to London.

533
00:29:01,267 --> 00:29:04,967
Now we know the date of Akmal's
death was important to her.

534
00:29:05,100 --> 00:29:07,200
I think this could be it.

535
00:29:07,333 --> 00:29:08,433
-She felt sorry for him.

536
00:29:08,567 --> 00:29:10,600
-Or maybe it was guilt
she felt.

537
00:29:10,733 --> 00:29:12,367
Maybe she knew
something about it.

538
00:29:12,500 --> 00:29:14,067
Maybe she knew the truth,

539
00:29:14,133 --> 00:29:17,600
and maybe that's
what got her killed.

540
00:29:18,700 --> 00:29:20,933
-That's a lot
of maybes in there.

541
00:29:23,133 --> 00:29:24,400
-[ Sighs ]

542
00:29:24,533 --> 00:29:26,800
-When was this?
-Ages ago.

543
00:29:26,933 --> 00:29:29,600
It was my first term at uni.
I was back home for a bit.

544
00:29:29,733 --> 00:29:31,733
-And did you see anything?

545
00:29:31,867 --> 00:29:34,100
-All I remember is
that Stella was around.

546
00:29:34,233 --> 00:29:37,067
A lot. At the kirk,
sometimes at the house.

547
00:29:37,200 --> 00:29:39,900
I didn't see anything, but
I spoke to Jean this morning,

548
00:29:40,067 --> 00:29:43,967
and apparently, she walked in
on Dad and Stella one day

549
00:29:44,100 --> 00:29:45,767
at the manse.

550
00:29:45,900 --> 00:29:49,500
And that's, I think, what put
an end to their relationship.

551
00:29:49,633 --> 00:29:51,233
-How long did it go on for?

552
00:29:51,367 --> 00:29:53,800
-Couple of months.
Two at the most.

553
00:29:53,933 --> 00:29:55,567
One day, Stella just
stopped coming.

554
00:29:55,700 --> 00:29:58,200
-Why?
-No idea.

555
00:29:58,333 --> 00:30:01,667
Next time I saw her, she was
at the church marrying Kieran.

556
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:03,267
-Did he ever say
anything about her?

557
00:30:03,400 --> 00:30:05,033
-God, no.

558
00:30:05,167 --> 00:30:07,733
He did keep his distance from
the Bains after that, though.

559
00:30:07,867 --> 00:30:09,700
-Why?

560
00:30:09,833 --> 00:30:12,500
-You have no business
being in there, and...

561
00:30:12,633 --> 00:30:14,833
-What the hell?
-I'm not putting up with it!

562
00:30:14,967 --> 00:30:17,133
This is outrageous!
Get out my house!

563
00:30:17,267 --> 00:30:19,733
-I didn't mean to upset you.
-What's going on?

564
00:30:19,867 --> 00:30:22,167
-He's trying to blacken
my brother's name!

565
00:30:22,300 --> 00:30:23,633
Body's not even cold,

566
00:30:23,767 --> 00:30:25,033
and this bastard's
accusing him of dealing!

567
00:30:25,167 --> 00:30:27,000
-I didn't say
that Cal was dealing.

568
00:30:27,133 --> 00:30:30,200
-Bullshit! He's just asked me
if I ever saw him with pills.

569
00:30:30,333 --> 00:30:33,733
-What? Why would you ask that?
-Let's talk about it later.

570
00:30:33,867 --> 00:30:35,233
-There's nothing
to talk about.

571
00:30:35,367 --> 00:30:36,900
-Why would you ask
if Cal was dealing?

572
00:30:37,033 --> 00:30:39,700
-I found these in his room.

573
00:30:39,833 --> 00:30:42,367
New drugs started coming
onto the Isles a few months ago.

574
00:30:42,500 --> 00:30:43,833
We've no idea
who's behind it,

575
00:30:43,967 --> 00:30:47,133
but whoever it is,
they use bags like these.

576
00:30:47,267 --> 00:30:49,467
-That's it?
That's all you've got?

577
00:30:49,600 --> 00:30:52,833
-Well, he's got a point.
It's not much.

578
00:30:52,967 --> 00:30:54,500
-The pills are sourced
in Aberdeen.

579
00:30:54,633 --> 00:30:56,900
My Drug Squad contact
down there confirmed it.

580
00:30:57,033 --> 00:31:00,600
And I have a witness who says
the pills come in every month --

581
00:31:00,733 --> 00:31:02,333
regular, which means --

582
00:31:02,467 --> 00:31:05,900
-Yes, all right. I get it.

583
00:31:06,067 --> 00:31:08,967
Could you... could you
give us a minute?

584
00:31:10,767 --> 00:31:11,467
Yeah.

585
00:31:11,600 --> 00:31:13,800
[ Footsteps retreating ]

586
00:31:13,933 --> 00:31:16,400
-I remember Sandy Wilson
when he was at school.

587
00:31:16,533 --> 00:31:19,567
He was a wee shit then
and he's a wee shit now.

588
00:31:19,700 --> 00:31:22,933
-James, how often was Cal
taking your stock to Aberdeen?

589
00:31:23,067 --> 00:31:26,067
-Oh, I don't know.
Not that often.

590
00:31:26,200 --> 00:31:28,767
-Once a month?

591
00:31:28,900 --> 00:31:30,300
-You're taking
his side on this!

592
00:31:30,433 --> 00:31:32,900
-I'm not taking
anyone's side.

593
00:31:33,067 --> 00:31:35,233
Sandy might've jumped
the gun a bit.

594
00:31:35,367 --> 00:31:36,767
I know that Cal
was up to something.

595
00:31:36,900 --> 00:31:38,267
Let's face it.

596
00:31:38,400 --> 00:31:40,200
It's not really
a surprise, is it?

597
00:31:40,333 --> 00:31:43,067
-My brother was a good guy.

598
00:31:43,167 --> 00:31:46,667
-Yeah, he tried to be.

599
00:31:46,800 --> 00:31:49,567
Look, none of this
is important right now.

600
00:31:49,700 --> 00:31:51,500
I'll talk to Sandy.

601
00:31:51,633 --> 00:31:54,667
-It's Neil Bain
you want to talk to.

602
00:31:54,800 --> 00:31:56,467
-Why do I need
to talk to Neil Bain?

603
00:31:56,600 --> 00:31:58,367
-He was always
hanging around here.

604
00:31:58,500 --> 00:32:00,567
I told Cal to stay clear.

605
00:32:00,700 --> 00:32:02,800
If there's dealing,
he'll be behind it.

606
00:32:02,933 --> 00:32:04,200
[ Scoffs ]

607
00:32:04,333 --> 00:32:06,567
Him and the other one
were here the other day.

608
00:32:06,700 --> 00:32:08,767
Couple of fly men.
-What other one?

609
00:32:08,900 --> 00:32:10,967
-Think I'm bloody stupid.

610
00:32:11,100 --> 00:32:13,700
-James, what other one?

611
00:32:13,833 --> 00:32:15,867
-Bobby Bain.

612
00:32:19,733 --> 00:32:22,233
-Alan, will you stay
with James?

613
00:32:22,367 --> 00:32:24,833
We need to find Neil Bain.

614
00:32:28,467 --> 00:32:31,667
-Wait, we're looking
for him because...?

615
00:32:31,800 --> 00:32:33,067
-Because I want to know why

616
00:32:33,200 --> 00:32:35,933
he and Bobby Bain
were up here with Cal.

617
00:32:36,067 --> 00:32:37,233
Keys?

618
00:32:37,367 --> 00:32:39,067
-Maybe we should
let Tosh know.

619
00:32:39,167 --> 00:32:41,700
-Why? Er, do you need
to ask her permission?

620
00:32:41,833 --> 00:32:45,733
-No. I just think I should call
her and keep her up to speed.

621
00:32:45,867 --> 00:32:47,367
-Fine, go ahead.
Do that, then.

622
00:32:47,500 --> 00:32:50,600
I'd hate for you
to get a row.

623
00:32:50,733 --> 00:32:52,900
-That's not going to work.

624
00:32:53,067 --> 00:32:54,200
I'm not 12.

625
00:32:54,333 --> 00:32:55,600
-[ Sighs ]

626
00:32:57,533 --> 00:33:01,333
-[ Sighs ] Christ.

627
00:33:01,467 --> 00:33:02,767
I'll do the talking.

628
00:33:02,900 --> 00:33:05,367
-Fine, but I'll do
the driving.

629
00:33:05,500 --> 00:33:06,733
Keys?

630
00:33:08,433 --> 00:33:10,133
[ Car lock beeps ]

631
00:33:15,700 --> 00:33:17,967
[ Sheep bleating ]

632
00:33:22,367 --> 00:33:32,233
♪♪

633
00:33:32,367 --> 00:33:34,300
-Hey, you all right?

634
00:33:34,433 --> 00:33:40,900
♪♪

635
00:33:41,067 --> 00:33:47,300
♪♪

636
00:33:47,433 --> 00:33:49,533
-Have you seen this?

637
00:33:53,167 --> 00:33:55,833
-Don't worry about it.
-Don't worry about it?

638
00:33:55,967 --> 00:33:58,433
It says that Ellen
and the Strachan girl

639
00:33:58,567 --> 00:34:02,367
were in a cult
with this... freak.

640
00:34:02,500 --> 00:34:04,167
-Ellen wasn't
into that stuff.

641
00:34:04,300 --> 00:34:06,200
-How would you know?

642
00:34:06,333 --> 00:34:09,633
-She was a lot of things,
but she wasn't stupid.

643
00:34:13,133 --> 00:34:16,133
-So, what about last night?

644
00:34:17,533 --> 00:34:19,133
-What do you mean?
-What do I mean?

645
00:34:19,267 --> 00:34:24,467
I mean, what the hell
happened with Cal Innes?

646
00:34:24,600 --> 00:34:26,667
-I don't know.

647
00:34:26,800 --> 00:34:29,567
-A man dies after spending
the night drinking with you,

648
00:34:29,700 --> 00:34:31,900
and all you can say is,
"I don't know"?

649
00:34:32,067 --> 00:34:33,867
-What else
do you want me to say?

650
00:34:34,067 --> 00:34:35,133
-[ Scoffs ]

651
00:34:35,267 --> 00:34:38,067
You don't seem
too concerned.

652
00:34:40,667 --> 00:34:42,933
-Stella and Kieran
seem better.

653
00:34:43,067 --> 00:34:44,933
-Better how?

654
00:34:45,067 --> 00:34:46,767
-Well, they're talking
for a start.

655
00:34:46,900 --> 00:34:51,833
-Aye, well, let's hope
he can talk some sense into her.

656
00:34:51,967 --> 00:34:56,333
That girl needs reminding
who her family is.

657
00:34:56,467 --> 00:34:57,967
-What's that supposed
to mean?

658
00:34:58,100 --> 00:35:02,133
-It means she had no right
breaking bread with the Knoxes.

659
00:35:02,267 --> 00:35:04,533
-"Breaking bread"?

660
00:35:04,667 --> 00:35:07,500
[ Chuckling ]
Are you serious?

661
00:35:07,633 --> 00:35:09,500
She went over
to talk to the boy.

662
00:35:09,633 --> 00:35:11,100
-You're defending her?

663
00:35:11,233 --> 00:35:13,267
-She just lost
her daughter!

664
00:35:13,400 --> 00:35:15,800
-And that means
we have to hand over

665
00:35:15,933 --> 00:35:17,167
everything
we've worked for?

666
00:35:17,300 --> 00:35:19,333
-Everything I worked for!

667
00:35:19,467 --> 00:35:20,800
Me!

668
00:35:23,933 --> 00:35:26,133
Don't worry.

669
00:35:26,267 --> 00:35:28,767
There's nothing left
for us to hand over.

670
00:35:28,900 --> 00:35:35,067
♪♪

671
00:35:35,200 --> 00:35:37,933
-Right, Lou, what are you
thinking about a wee bun

672
00:35:38,067 --> 00:35:40,067
for the way home, eh?

673
00:35:40,133 --> 00:35:41,733
Huh? That sound good?

674
00:35:41,867 --> 00:35:43,600
[ Chuckles ]

675
00:35:45,167 --> 00:35:46,933
Oh.

676
00:35:47,067 --> 00:35:48,167
Farida.

677
00:35:48,300 --> 00:35:54,867
♪♪

678
00:35:55,067 --> 00:35:56,200
Are you all right?

679
00:35:56,333 --> 00:36:01,700
♪♪

680
00:36:01,833 --> 00:36:06,800
♪♪

681
00:36:06,933 --> 00:36:08,067
-[ Sighs ]

682
00:36:08,200 --> 00:36:09,900
[ Mobile rings ]

683
00:36:11,967 --> 00:36:13,067
Hey.

684
00:36:15,300 --> 00:36:17,867
[ Dog barking ]

685
00:36:18,067 --> 00:36:19,533
-Remember,
I'll do the talking.

686
00:36:19,667 --> 00:36:22,267
-Understood.
-You're just here to observe.

687
00:36:22,400 --> 00:36:24,167
-Seen and not heard.

688
00:36:24,300 --> 00:36:26,133
-That's the gist of it.

689
00:36:26,267 --> 00:36:27,933
[ Knock on door ]

690
00:36:30,600 --> 00:36:32,633
-DI Calder.
Mind if we come in?

691
00:36:34,767 --> 00:36:38,400
We need to talk to you about
your relationship with Cal.

692
00:36:41,300 --> 00:36:42,500
-Cal?

693
00:36:42,633 --> 00:36:46,333
-Cal Innes.
You two were friends.

694
00:36:46,467 --> 00:36:48,933
-Not really.
I knew him, that's all.

695
00:36:49,067 --> 00:36:51,067
-"Knew him"?!

696
00:36:52,100 --> 00:36:54,700
So, you heard he died?

697
00:36:54,833 --> 00:36:57,800
-Yeah, he was in
an accident.

698
00:36:57,933 --> 00:37:00,400
-Who told you
it was an accident?

699
00:37:00,533 --> 00:37:02,233
-[ Scoffs ]

700
00:37:02,367 --> 00:37:05,400
I don't -- I don't know.
I ju-- I just heard.

701
00:37:05,533 --> 00:37:07,600
-When did you last
speak to Cal?

702
00:37:07,733 --> 00:37:10,733
-Er, I don't know.

703
00:37:10,867 --> 00:37:12,433
Ages ago.

704
00:37:12,567 --> 00:37:15,100
We weren't that close.
I never really knew him.

705
00:37:15,233 --> 00:37:18,167
-Really? Hmm.

706
00:37:18,300 --> 00:37:21,767
'Cos his brother said that you
and him were dealing together.

707
00:37:21,900 --> 00:37:26,067
-Dealing?
Dealing what?

708
00:37:26,200 --> 00:37:29,700
-Pills. The ones that Cal was
bringing in from the Mainland

709
00:37:29,833 --> 00:37:30,967
every month.

710
00:37:31,100 --> 00:37:33,967
-I don't know
anything about that.

711
00:37:34,100 --> 00:37:36,800
-Okay. Right.

712
00:37:36,933 --> 00:37:38,733
Well, here's
what we'll do, then.

713
00:37:38,867 --> 00:37:40,933
DC Wilson here's
going to call in a Search team.

714
00:37:41,067 --> 00:37:42,967
We'll get them
to go over the place,

715
00:37:43,100 --> 00:37:44,467
and while
they're doing that,

716
00:37:44,600 --> 00:37:46,067
we'll get the IT team
from Inverness,

717
00:37:46,167 --> 00:37:48,067
they'll start going
through your calls, texts,

718
00:37:48,200 --> 00:37:49,833
chats, internet history...

719
00:37:49,967 --> 00:37:51,533
-What? I haven't
done anything.

720
00:37:51,667 --> 00:37:54,667
-Well, you have nothing
to worry about, then, have you?

721
00:37:55,733 --> 00:37:57,500
But then, of course,
there's the witness.

722
00:37:57,633 --> 00:37:58,933
-What witness?

723
00:37:59,067 --> 00:38:02,733
-Oh, the -- the one
that DC Wilson found.

724
00:38:04,133 --> 00:38:06,333
The one who identified you

725
00:38:06,467 --> 00:38:09,067
as the person
that sold them the pills.

726
00:38:09,167 --> 00:38:10,433
-[ Sighs ]

727
00:38:12,400 --> 00:38:16,467
Look, I didn't sell them.

728
00:38:16,600 --> 00:38:18,067
Maybe gave a few away,

729
00:38:18,200 --> 00:38:20,833
but Cal was the one
that brought them up here.

730
00:38:20,967 --> 00:38:22,333
-So, it was you and Cal?

731
00:38:22,467 --> 00:38:23,367
-Mostly Cal.

732
00:38:23,500 --> 00:38:26,067
-What about Bobby?

733
00:38:28,067 --> 00:38:32,167
Look, we know that you and him
spoke with Cal yesterday.

734
00:38:32,300 --> 00:38:34,567
We know that Cal was up
at the Bain farm last night,

735
00:38:34,700 --> 00:38:36,367
so you need to start
by telling me

736
00:38:36,500 --> 00:38:38,967
what Bobby Bain's part
in all of this is!

737
00:38:39,100 --> 00:38:43,833
-Bobby didn't have
a part in this.

738
00:38:43,967 --> 00:38:45,733
-Make the call.
-No, no. Wait, wait.

739
00:38:45,867 --> 00:38:47,733
Right.

740
00:38:47,867 --> 00:38:50,200
Okay. Fine.

741
00:38:50,333 --> 00:38:54,200
♪♪

742
00:38:54,333 --> 00:38:55,500
[ Sighs ]

743
00:38:55,633 --> 00:38:57,867
Bobby only got onboard
a few days ago.

744
00:38:58,067 --> 00:39:00,133
-Came onboard how?

745
00:39:00,267 --> 00:39:01,800
-He said he had some money.

746
00:39:01,933 --> 00:39:05,900
He wanted us to bring in
a bigger stash, but Cal refused.

747
00:39:06,067 --> 00:39:07,433
He turned Bobby down.

748
00:39:07,567 --> 00:39:11,067
-So, why were Cal and Bobby
together last night?

749
00:39:11,200 --> 00:39:13,733
-I -- I don't know.

750
00:39:13,867 --> 00:39:15,833
-How much money
are we talking?

751
00:39:15,967 --> 00:39:17,867
-Looked like a lot.

752
00:39:18,067 --> 00:39:19,400
-So you saw it?

753
00:39:19,533 --> 00:39:20,800
-Yeah.

754
00:39:20,933 --> 00:39:23,933
It was in a bag,
full of cash.

755
00:39:24,067 --> 00:39:25,233
Thousands, I reckon.

756
00:39:25,367 --> 00:39:33,367
♪♪

757
00:39:33,500 --> 00:39:34,933
[ Door closes ]
[ Sighs ]

758
00:39:35,067 --> 00:39:36,667
-[ Singing ]
* Where's your foot gone? *

759
00:39:36,800 --> 00:39:38,100
* Where's your foot? *

760
00:39:39,733 --> 00:39:41,933
Oh, here's Mummy.

761
00:39:50,400 --> 00:39:52,967
Hey.
-Hi.

762
00:39:53,100 --> 00:39:54,467
[ Sighs ]

763
00:39:54,600 --> 00:39:56,733
Where is she?
-[ Sighs ]

764
00:39:58,833 --> 00:40:00,200
[ Louise coos ]

765
00:40:00,333 --> 00:40:02,167
-Says she wants
to speak to you.

766
00:40:02,300 --> 00:40:05,400
But, Tosh, like,
go easy, would you?

767
00:40:05,533 --> 00:40:07,567
-Yeah.
-Okay.

768
00:40:19,500 --> 00:40:21,733
-How are you doing,
Farida?

769
00:40:29,567 --> 00:40:32,333
Donnie says
you wanted to see me?

770
00:40:35,900 --> 00:40:39,400
-He learned to ride
his bike here.

771
00:40:39,533 --> 00:40:42,467
Me and Azir brought him.

772
00:40:42,600 --> 00:40:44,333
It was orange,
the bike.

773
00:40:44,467 --> 00:40:47,633
He loved it.
And he was so quick.

774
00:40:47,767 --> 00:40:51,133
One lesson and he was racing
around us, laughing.

775
00:40:51,267 --> 00:40:53,000
[ Breathes deeply ]

776
00:40:54,233 --> 00:40:57,667
I can still smell him.

777
00:40:57,800 --> 00:41:01,167
If I close my eyes
and focus,

778
00:41:01,300 --> 00:41:05,800
I can smell the heat
on his hair.

779
00:41:05,933 --> 00:41:07,067
[ Sobs ]

780
00:41:09,367 --> 00:41:11,467
It was my fault.

781
00:41:12,867 --> 00:41:15,433
-What was your fault,
Farida?

782
00:41:18,200 --> 00:41:21,167
I fell asleep.

783
00:41:21,300 --> 00:41:22,733
I was so tired.

784
00:41:22,867 --> 00:41:26,600
And Azir had given me
these new tablets,

785
00:41:26,733 --> 00:41:28,133
but I must've
taken too many

786
00:41:28,267 --> 00:41:32,633
or maybe I forgot
and I'd taken some before.

787
00:41:32,767 --> 00:41:35,600
I struggle with my moods.

788
00:41:35,733 --> 00:41:39,633
Azir helps me
manage them.

789
00:41:39,767 --> 00:41:43,300
I only woke up because
she was screaming, Ellen,

790
00:41:43,433 --> 00:41:44,500
in the garden.

791
00:41:44,633 --> 00:41:48,100
And Heather was leaning
over me.

792
00:41:48,233 --> 00:41:49,700
Shaking me.

793
00:41:49,833 --> 00:41:52,733
I couldn't get
my head to work.

794
00:41:52,867 --> 00:41:54,300
And she was saying,
"It's Akmal."

795
00:41:54,433 --> 00:41:58,100
And I said, "No.
He's in his room."

796
00:41:58,233 --> 00:42:03,933
And she said...
"Oh, Farida."

797
00:42:04,067 --> 00:42:06,800
And I saw why Ellen
was screaming.

798
00:42:08,167 --> 00:42:10,467
[ Sobbing ] She was at
the bottom of the garden...

799
00:42:10,600 --> 00:42:12,700
on her knees.

800
00:42:12,833 --> 00:42:15,567
And he was lying
across her.

801
00:42:20,467 --> 00:42:24,500
My beautiful boy...
had died...

802
00:42:24,633 --> 00:42:27,533
alone in that loch...

803
00:42:27,667 --> 00:42:30,067
and I'd slept through it.

804
00:42:33,200 --> 00:42:35,567
-Farida...

805
00:42:35,700 --> 00:42:39,100
I am so sorry
this happened.

806
00:42:40,667 --> 00:42:44,333
I have to ask you
a few things, okay?

807
00:42:47,167 --> 00:42:51,500
What happened after Heather
and Ellen found Akmal?

808
00:42:51,633 --> 00:42:55,567
-Azir came home, and he was
crying and shouting at me.

809
00:42:55,700 --> 00:42:58,467
Saying it was all my fault.

810
00:43:00,667 --> 00:43:04,433
-What happened then?

811
00:43:04,567 --> 00:43:06,400
-She took over.

812
00:43:06,533 --> 00:43:09,767
Heather told Azir
to call the ambulance.

813
00:43:09,900 --> 00:43:14,067
She told him to tell them that
he was there when it happened.

814
00:43:14,200 --> 00:43:18,267
We would say, we took our eyes
off him for a few minutes,

815
00:43:18,400 --> 00:43:22,167
and he must've got into
the garden and into the loch...

816
00:43:22,300 --> 00:43:25,400
-Why? Why were you
to say that?

817
00:43:25,533 --> 00:43:27,867
-Because she said
we'd lose it all.

818
00:43:29,533 --> 00:43:34,067
The pills.
They weren't prescribed.

819
00:43:34,167 --> 00:43:37,267
Azir was giving them to me.

820
00:43:37,400 --> 00:43:39,600
He'd lose his job.

821
00:43:39,733 --> 00:43:43,767
I'd be prosecuted, and they'd
take Zuma away from us.

822
00:43:43,900 --> 00:43:48,100
So, we lied...
to everyone.

823
00:43:51,067 --> 00:43:54,367
We betrayed our boy.

824
00:43:54,500 --> 00:43:57,067
-Come here. Come here.

825
00:43:57,167 --> 00:44:00,433
-[ Sobbing ]

826
00:44:00,567 --> 00:44:03,067
-It's all right.
It's all right.

827
00:44:03,200 --> 00:44:09,967
♪♪

828
00:44:10,100 --> 00:44:11,800
-Farida?

829
00:44:11,933 --> 00:44:15,567
Where are you?
I'm getting worried.

830
00:44:15,700 --> 00:44:17,167
You -- you need the --

831
00:44:17,300 --> 00:44:18,800
[ Vehicle approaching ]

832
00:44:18,933 --> 00:44:24,633
♪♪

833
00:44:24,767 --> 00:44:30,300
♪♪

834
00:44:30,433 --> 00:44:32,333
-It has to be
Ellen's money.

835
00:44:32,467 --> 00:44:33,900
-We don't know that
for sure.

836
00:44:34,067 --> 00:44:35,600
-Well, we know the Bains
are struggling.

837
00:44:35,733 --> 00:44:37,767
The farm hasn't
made profit for years.

838
00:44:37,900 --> 00:44:41,133
I mean, come on, where's
Bobby Bain going to find cash

839
00:44:41,267 --> 00:44:42,533
to get into
the drug business?

840
00:44:42,667 --> 00:44:44,467
-Look, even if it is
Ellen's money,

841
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:46,467
she lost it
before she was killed.

842
00:44:46,600 --> 00:44:49,600
-Says Howell.
Maybe she lied to him.

843
00:44:49,733 --> 00:44:52,767
Maybe she picked up the money
after she got away from them.

844
00:44:52,900 --> 00:44:55,567
She runs into Bobby
and he kills her for it.

845
00:44:55,700 --> 00:44:58,233
Maybe that is what Cal
found out last night.

846
00:44:58,367 --> 00:44:59,833
And if Cal was onto Bobby,

847
00:45:00,067 --> 00:45:01,800
that's reason enough
for him to want him dead.

848
00:45:01,933 --> 00:45:03,867
-Well, first, we need to prove
that it is Ellen's money.

849
00:45:04,067 --> 00:45:06,700
I mean, Bobby could've got it
from another source.

850
00:45:06,833 --> 00:45:09,233
-Then we need to access
his bank records.

851
00:45:09,367 --> 00:45:10,967
-Then you'll need
to talk to Tosh.

852
00:45:11,100 --> 00:45:12,367
-Sandy!

853
00:45:12,500 --> 00:45:15,167
-This has gone too far.

854
00:45:19,667 --> 00:45:21,900
-He was there
because of me.

855
00:45:22,067 --> 00:45:26,733
♪♪

856
00:45:26,867 --> 00:45:31,167
Cal went to see Bobby because
I needed to know something.

857
00:45:31,300 --> 00:45:34,433
Just something
I can't tell you about, but...

858
00:45:34,567 --> 00:45:35,900
[ Sighs ]

859
00:45:36,067 --> 00:45:37,200
He went there last night

860
00:45:37,333 --> 00:45:39,700
because he was wanting
to help me.

861
00:45:41,333 --> 00:45:44,267
And now, he's dead.

862
00:45:44,400 --> 00:45:49,167
That... stupid, infuriating,
drug-dealing arsehole is dead,

863
00:45:49,300 --> 00:45:53,300
and I'm pretty sure
that it's my fault.

864
00:45:53,433 --> 00:45:58,333
♪♪

865
00:45:58,467 --> 00:46:02,100
So, I really need
to do this.

866
00:46:02,233 --> 00:46:04,767
Do you understand?

867
00:46:08,633 --> 00:46:11,100
-I'll see what I can do.

868
00:46:14,433 --> 00:46:15,367
Okay.

869
00:46:15,500 --> 00:46:23,433
♪♪

870
00:46:23,567 --> 00:46:26,167
-I want you to know
that I only did what I did

871
00:46:26,300 --> 00:46:29,367
to keep my family.

872
00:46:29,500 --> 00:46:32,100
-You lied about
your son's death.

873
00:46:34,100 --> 00:46:35,567
-We were in shock,

874
00:46:35,700 --> 00:46:37,967
and Heather was making
all the decisions.

875
00:46:38,100 --> 00:46:39,767
We were frightened.

876
00:46:39,900 --> 00:46:42,633
-What did Ellen
think about it?

877
00:46:42,767 --> 00:46:44,667
-I think she wanted
to tell the truth,

878
00:46:44,800 --> 00:46:48,067
but Heather
wouldn't let her.

879
00:46:48,200 --> 00:46:50,533
Heather controlled it all.

880
00:46:50,667 --> 00:46:53,733
As soon as we started lying,
she had us.

881
00:46:53,867 --> 00:46:55,667
-Had you?

882
00:46:55,800 --> 00:46:57,133
In what way?

883
00:46:57,267 --> 00:46:59,700
-It started just
after the memorial.

884
00:46:59,833 --> 00:47:02,200
Said she needed some money.

885
00:47:02,333 --> 00:47:04,900
Made it sound like
it was a loan.

886
00:47:05,067 --> 00:47:07,900
-She blackmailed you?

887
00:47:08,067 --> 00:47:10,200
-Has been ever since.

888
00:47:12,233 --> 00:47:13,600
-[ Sighs ]

889
00:47:13,733 --> 00:47:17,533
Even so, that still
doesn't change the fact

890
00:47:17,667 --> 00:47:20,067
that you and Farida lied.

891
00:47:23,100 --> 00:47:24,967
-It was an accident.

892
00:47:25,100 --> 00:47:27,367
A tragedy
we'll never get over.

893
00:47:27,500 --> 00:47:30,300
How it happened?
Why it happened?

894
00:47:30,433 --> 00:47:32,533
Just details.

895
00:47:35,100 --> 00:47:38,433
-Akmal was your family.

896
00:47:38,567 --> 00:47:40,800
He was your son.

897
00:47:40,933 --> 00:47:44,600
And he deserved better
than a sordid cover-up.

898
00:47:45,833 --> 00:47:50,533
Those details you talk about
were the record of his passing,

899
00:47:50,667 --> 00:47:56,433
and they should have been
treated with the proper respect.

900
00:47:56,567 --> 00:47:57,633
-[ Sighs ]

901
00:47:57,767 --> 00:48:03,167
♪♪

902
00:48:03,300 --> 00:48:05,833
-I don't understand
how we missed this.

903
00:48:05,967 --> 00:48:08,933
They were interviewed. Social
Services investigated them.

904
00:48:09,067 --> 00:48:13,400
-It was an awful thing,
and it happened to nice people.

905
00:48:13,533 --> 00:48:15,567
Nobody wants
to think the worst.

906
00:48:15,700 --> 00:48:18,800
-We'll need
to reopen the case.

907
00:48:18,933 --> 00:48:22,067
-Farida Sadat's statement.
-Thanks.

908
00:48:22,133 --> 00:48:25,467
Now, can you tell Grant to go
and secure the Sadat house?

909
00:48:25,600 --> 00:48:27,367
Let us know if Forensics
find anything.

910
00:48:27,500 --> 00:48:29,167
-Sure. Why are you
going over the house?

911
00:48:29,300 --> 00:48:31,267
-I want their car
processed, too.

912
00:48:31,400 --> 00:48:33,967
-But they've already
admitted to it.

913
00:48:34,100 --> 00:48:35,667
-I know.

914
00:48:35,800 --> 00:48:37,333
-If you're looking
for evidence of Akmal's death,

915
00:48:37,467 --> 00:48:40,067
it was months --
-This isn't about Akmal.

916
00:48:40,167 --> 00:48:43,067
It's about Ellen.

917
00:48:43,133 --> 00:48:44,667
Azir just admitted

918
00:48:44,800 --> 00:48:46,967
that Ellen wanted to tell
the truth about the accident,

919
00:48:47,100 --> 00:48:50,700
and we know she tried
to call him on the day she died.

920
00:48:50,833 --> 00:48:55,167
Ellen was a threat
to the Sadats.

921
00:48:55,300 --> 00:48:56,600
You call me
if they find anything?

922
00:48:56,733 --> 00:48:58,333
-Aye. Where will you be?

923
00:48:58,467 --> 00:49:00,700
-With Heather Bain.

924
00:49:03,767 --> 00:49:06,500
-Bobby's bank records
have just come through.

925
00:49:06,633 --> 00:49:10,067
This guy's broke.

926
00:49:10,200 --> 00:49:12,067
-Does it -- I mean, there's no
way Bobby Bain's managed

927
00:49:12,133 --> 00:49:13,967
to raise thousands
off his own back.

928
00:49:14,100 --> 00:49:15,800
-Ah, doesn't mean
he got it from Ellen.

929
00:49:15,933 --> 00:49:17,400
-No, but the odds
are shortening.

930
00:49:17,533 --> 00:49:19,567
-There you are.
[ Plates clink ]

931
00:49:20,767 --> 00:49:22,300
-Even if he is struggling,

932
00:49:22,433 --> 00:49:24,500
would he really kill
his own niece for money?

933
00:49:24,633 --> 00:49:27,667
I mean, the Bains...
-These are London transactions.

934
00:49:27,800 --> 00:49:28,900
-What?

935
00:49:29,067 --> 00:49:31,567
-All of these
debit card payments.

936
00:49:31,700 --> 00:49:37,067
Er, last transaction
was the 18th of April.

937
00:49:37,133 --> 00:49:40,300
That is three days
before Ellen came back.

938
00:49:40,433 --> 00:49:42,567
-Bobby was in London?

939
00:49:42,700 --> 00:49:44,800
-I need to make
a phone call.

940
00:49:46,167 --> 00:49:47,900
[ Vehicle approaches ]

941
00:49:51,500 --> 00:49:53,333
[ Car door slams ]

942
00:49:54,067 --> 00:49:57,267
-They lost a child!

943
00:49:57,400 --> 00:49:59,400
A five-year-old son.

944
00:49:59,533 --> 00:50:03,067
And what did you do?
You blackmailed them.

945
00:50:03,200 --> 00:50:06,133
-[ Scoffs ] Don't know
what you're on about.

946
00:50:06,267 --> 00:50:09,967
-No, don't give me that.
Farida told me everything.

947
00:50:10,100 --> 00:50:13,900
-Oh, I wouldn't put too much
store in what Farida says.

948
00:50:14,033 --> 00:50:15,467
She gets confused.

949
00:50:15,600 --> 00:50:17,767
-Don't you dare!

950
00:50:17,900 --> 00:50:20,067
You don't get to make
judgments on anyone,

951
00:50:20,200 --> 00:50:22,567
not after what you did.

952
00:50:22,700 --> 00:50:24,833
-What I did? [ Chuckles ]

953
00:50:24,967 --> 00:50:27,533
Oh, aye, you're full
of sympathy for her now,

954
00:50:27,667 --> 00:50:29,400
but would you lot
have been so understanding

955
00:50:29,533 --> 00:50:31,133
if you'd turned up
that day?

956
00:50:31,267 --> 00:50:34,600
A kid in the loch and a mother
blasted out of her mind.

957
00:50:34,733 --> 00:50:36,700
She told you
what happened?

958
00:50:36,833 --> 00:50:38,833
Farida doesn't remember
what happened.

959
00:50:38,967 --> 00:50:41,400
-She remembers
you extorted them.

960
00:50:41,533 --> 00:50:45,000
-I didn't extort anyone.

961
00:50:45,133 --> 00:50:46,933
But do you know what?

962
00:50:47,067 --> 00:50:48,600
Maybe I should have,

963
00:50:48,733 --> 00:50:51,433
because without me,
they'd have lost everything.

964
00:50:51,567 --> 00:50:55,167
I did a good thing.
-[ Scoffs ]

965
00:50:55,300 --> 00:50:57,800
And what about Ellen?
-What about her?

966
00:50:57,933 --> 00:50:59,700
-Where were you
when she needed you?

967
00:50:59,833 --> 00:51:01,733
When she was struggling
with what happened.

968
00:51:01,867 --> 00:51:04,600
What did you do then?
-I was always there for Ellen.

969
00:51:04,733 --> 00:51:08,167
-You sent her to Langbank.
-Because she needed help.

970
00:51:08,300 --> 00:51:10,633
-Because you needed
to shut her up.

971
00:51:10,767 --> 00:51:12,500
You handed her over
to Azir Sadat

972
00:51:12,633 --> 00:51:15,633
because you wanted him to find
a way to keep her from talking.

973
00:51:15,767 --> 00:51:17,900
-Ellen was never
going to talk.

974
00:51:18,067 --> 00:51:21,133
She didn't break down
because of Akmal.

975
00:51:21,267 --> 00:51:25,500
Aye, she was upset.
We all were.

976
00:51:25,633 --> 00:51:28,067
That's not why she left.

977
00:51:28,200 --> 00:51:29,833
-Then why did she leave?

978
00:51:29,967 --> 00:51:32,400
-Who knows?!

979
00:51:32,533 --> 00:51:34,367
And who cares?

980
00:51:34,500 --> 00:51:36,400
Ellen was a nightmare.

981
00:51:36,533 --> 00:51:38,733
I was glad to see
the back of her.

982
00:51:38,867 --> 00:51:44,967
♪♪

983
00:51:45,100 --> 00:51:50,067
♪♪

984
00:51:50,200 --> 00:51:51,700
[ Mobile ringing ]

985
00:51:51,833 --> 00:51:56,133
♪♪

986
00:51:56,267 --> 00:51:58,100
-Alex?

987
00:51:58,233 --> 00:52:00,100
-Forensics have
found something.

988
00:52:00,233 --> 00:52:01,933
[ Police radio chatter ]

989
00:52:05,333 --> 00:52:06,600
-Here you go.

990
00:52:09,133 --> 00:52:11,833
-So, I've just spoken
to my DC.

991
00:52:11,967 --> 00:52:13,467
I'd asked him to check
with Ellen's flatmate

992
00:52:13,600 --> 00:52:15,067
to see if she could confirm

993
00:52:15,133 --> 00:52:16,833
that Bobby Bain was at Ellen's
on the 18th.

994
00:52:16,967 --> 00:52:19,700
-And?
-And she couldn't.

995
00:52:19,833 --> 00:52:21,733
-Well, then, that's that.
-Well, not quite.

996
00:52:21,867 --> 00:52:24,167
My DC found an incident
report from that day.

997
00:52:24,300 --> 00:52:27,667
A call-out to Ellen's flat.
Domestic disturbance.

998
00:52:27,800 --> 00:52:30,067
A neighbour called it in.
-Were there any details?

999
00:52:30,200 --> 00:52:33,400
-Oh, yes. She said that Ellen
was arguing with an older man,

1000
00:52:33,533 --> 00:52:35,367
but he'd gone by the time
the Uniforms showed up.

1001
00:52:35,500 --> 00:52:37,067
-Well, we don't know
it was Bobby.

1002
00:52:37,133 --> 00:52:39,233
-Yes, we do. The neighbour
snapped the guy on her phone

1003
00:52:39,367 --> 00:52:41,333
and my team
have ID'd Bobby.

1004
00:52:41,467 --> 00:52:46,133
♪♪

1005
00:52:46,267 --> 00:52:50,433
-Azir, I want to ask you about
the night Ellen Quinn died.

1006
00:52:50,567 --> 00:52:53,067
Did you have any contact
with her that night?

1007
00:52:56,967 --> 00:52:58,800
We found this blanket
in your car.

1008
00:52:58,933 --> 00:53:01,367
Can you confirm
it's yours, Azir?

1009
00:53:05,500 --> 00:53:07,733
The colour and the fabric
are similar

1010
00:53:07,867 --> 00:53:09,533
to fibres we found
in Ellen's hair.

1011
00:53:09,667 --> 00:53:11,433
You got any
thoughts on that?

1012
00:53:13,967 --> 00:53:15,567
-No.

1013
00:53:15,700 --> 00:53:20,667
-Well, we also found
blood traces in your car.

1014
00:53:22,200 --> 00:53:25,233
Our Forensic team believe
they're relatively fresh.

1015
00:53:25,367 --> 00:53:28,200
No more than, say,
a week old.

1016
00:53:28,333 --> 00:53:29,500
-I didn't kill her.

1017
00:53:29,633 --> 00:53:32,067
-But you were with her?
-Yes.

1018
00:53:32,200 --> 00:53:35,233
-On the night she died?

1019
00:53:35,367 --> 00:53:37,767
-When I didn't answer her call,
she came to the house.

1020
00:53:37,900 --> 00:53:39,167
-What time was that?

1021
00:53:39,300 --> 00:53:42,533
-It was late.
She was wet. Injured.

1022
00:53:42,667 --> 00:53:45,367
-Why did she come to you?

1023
00:53:45,500 --> 00:53:47,533
-She wanted money.

1024
00:53:47,667 --> 00:53:49,867
Said she was in trouble
and had to leave Shetland.

1025
00:53:50,067 --> 00:53:52,833
I told her I didn't have any.
She started getting angry.

1026
00:53:52,967 --> 00:53:55,233
Farida was asleep.
I -- I didn't want her upset.

1027
00:53:55,367 --> 00:53:56,833
-So, what did you do?

1028
00:53:56,967 --> 00:53:59,700
-I told her I'd try and get her
some in the morning.

1029
00:53:59,833 --> 00:54:01,733
And then she left.

1030
00:54:05,133 --> 00:54:09,367
-You told me Ellen wanted
to tell the truth about Akmal.

1031
00:54:09,500 --> 00:54:11,733
-We all did.
-But Heather stopped you?

1032
00:54:11,867 --> 00:54:13,100
-Yes.

1033
00:54:13,233 --> 00:54:15,800
-Still, if Ellen did choose
to come forward,

1034
00:54:15,933 --> 00:54:17,967
that would be a problem.

1035
00:54:18,100 --> 00:54:20,433
-I didn't kill Ellen.

1036
00:54:20,567 --> 00:54:23,733
-I don't believe you, Azir.

1037
